In [157]:
def print_path(l):
    for i in l:
        if i == l[len(l)-1]:
            print(i)
        else:
            print(f"{i} --> ", end="")
In [158]:
def find_lowest_cost_node(costs):
    lowest_cost = float("inf")
    lowest_cost_node = None
    # Go through each node.
    for node in costs:
        cost = costs[node]
        # If it's the lowest cost so far and hasn't been processed yet...
        if cost < lowest_cost and node not in processed:
            # ... set it as the new lowest-cost node.
            lowest_cost = cost
            lowest_cost_node = node
    return lowest_cost_node

def dikjstra(dest):
    # Find the lowest-cost node that you haven't processed yet.
    node = find_lowest_cost_node(costs)
    # If you've processed all the nodes, this while loop is done.
    while node is not None and node != dest:
        cost = costs[node]
        # Go through all the neighbors of this node.
        neighbors = graph[node]
        for n in neighbors.keys():
            new_cost = cost + neighbors[n]
            # If it's cheaper to get to this neighbor by going through this node...
            if costs[n] > new_cost:
                # ... update the cost for this node.
                costs[n] = new_cost
                # This node becomes the new parent for this neighbor.
                parents[n] = node
        # Mark the node as processed.
        processed.append(node)
        # Find the next node to process, and loop.
        node = find_lowest_cost_node(costs)

def bfs_search(dest):
    search_queue = deque()
    #changed from name to level 1 so it added the level 1 first to the queue before adding it's connections from before
    search_queue += graph2["Level 1"]
    # This array is how you keep track of which city you've searched before.
    searched = []
    while search_queue:
        print(search_queue)
        city = search_queue.popleft()
        # Only search this city if you haven't already searched them.
        if city not in searched:
            #when the city in the graph is found make sure it matches the name wanted
            if  city == dest:
                return True
            else:
                search_queue += graph2[city]
                # Marks this person as searched
                searched.append(city)
    return False

#get nodes form parents graph
def print_dfs_search():
    path = []
    node = "Los Angeles"
    while parents[node]:
        path.insert(0, node)
        node = parents[node]
        if node == "NYC":
            path.insert(0, node)
    return path

#get length of path
dkjnode = len(print_dfs_search())
#print it
print_path(print_dfs_search())
#display stops
str(dkjnode) + ' stops'

In this programming exericise we examine the shortest path using Breadth first search and Dijkstra's Algorithm. We first made a graph with weights for the Dijkstra's algorithm and made a graph like in the last programming assignment without the weights for Breadth First Seach.

From comparing the algorithms, the number of stops made is greater for Dijkstra's which has a total of 10 stops while Breadth First Search has 7 stops which is less. The path that Djikstra's algorithm is going from NYC --> DC --> Atlanta route, while Breadth First Search takes the NYC-->Indianapolis--->Denver route. It takes less hours to travel from New York City to Los Angeles which is 18 hours as this is the goal of Dijkstra's algorithm, while Breadth First Search takes 46 hours because it does not look at the weights but instead uses the path with the least amount of edges. In terms of complexity Dijkstra's algorithm takes less time since it does not have to look through all the nodes and just makes sure it looks through lowest cost nodes.

The algorthm complexity is O(E logV), because you are reducing the number of edges to look through by going to through the edges with less weights, but can get worst when you have graph where all nodes are not connected. In the case of Breadth First Search, it is going through all the nodes and edges and has a time of O(V + E).

Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26547816/understanding-time-complexity-calculation-for-dijkstra-algorithm
